tep but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
  ('CISA-00332', 3, 'Hard', 'System Development Methodologies', 'A company is developing a new e-commerce platform. The development team initially adopted a waterfall methodology. However, after several months, they realize that the initial requirements are rapidly changing due to evolving market trends and customer feedback. The IS auditor observes significant delays and cost overruns. Which of the following recommendations would be MOST appropriate for the IS auditor to suggest to address these challenges?', 'Force the development team to strictly adhere to the original requirements and timeline, as deviations will further exacerbate the delays and cost overruns.', 'Recommend switching to an agile methodology with short sprints, frequent feedback loops, and the ability to adapt to changing requirements.', 'Suggest outsourcing the remaining development work to a vendor with expertise in waterfall methodologies and a proven track record of delivering projects on time and within budget.', 'Advise the project manager to implement stricter change management procedures to control the scope and prevent further requirement changes.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Recommend switching to an agile methodology with short sprints, frequent feedback loops, and the ability to adapt to changing requirements.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Force the development team to strictly adhere to the original requirements and timeline, as deviations will further exacerbate the delays and cost overruns. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Suggest outsourcing the remaining development work to a vendor with expertise in waterfall methodologies and a proven track record of delivering projects on time and within budget. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Advise the project manager to implement stricter change management procedures to control the scope and prevent further requirement changes. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.', 'In a situation where requirements are rapidly changing, an agile methodology is the most suitable approach. It allows for flexibility, continuous feedback, and adaptation to new requirements throughout the development process, mitigating the risks associated with fixed requirements in a waterfall approach. This addresses the core issue of changing needs that caused the original problems.', 'See reasoning above for explanation of correct vs incorrect choices', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Recommend 