  ('CISA-00336', 1, 'Hard', 'Audit Reporting and Follow-up', 'During a follow-up audit, an IS auditor discovers that management has only partially implemented the recommendations from the previous audit report regarding a critical vulnerability in a web application. While the vulnerability was patched, the underlying coding flaw that caused the vulnerability was not addressed. What action should the IS auditor take FIRST?', 'Immediately issue a new report highlighting the non-compliance and escalate the issue to the audit committee.', 'Extend the scope of the follow-up audit to determine the potential impact of the unaddressed coding flaw.', 'Discuss the findings with management to understand the rationale for the partial implementation and any planned remediation efforts.', 'Update the risk assessment to reflect the residual risk associated with the unaddressed coding flaw.', 'C', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (C): Discuss the findings with management to understand the rationale for the partial implementation and any planned remediation efforts.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findin