  ('CISA-00338', 1, 'Hard', 'Professional Ethics and Standards', 'An IS auditor, during the course of an audit, discovers a significant fraud perpetrated by a close personal friend who is a senior manager within the organization. The fraud has material impact on the financial statements. Which of the following actions should the IS auditor take?', 'Discuss the findings with the friend and allow them an opportunity to rectify the situation before reporting it.', 'Disclose the potential conflict of interest to the audit committee and recuse themselves from further involvement in the audit.', 'Report the fraud to the appropriate authorities within the organization, regardless of the personal relationship.', 'Adjust the audit report to mitigate the impact of the fraud on the overall assessment of the organization''s internal controls.', 'C', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (C): Report the fraud to the appropriate authorities within the organization, regardless of the personal relationship.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Discuss the findings with the friend and allow them an opportunity to rectify the situation before reporting it. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option B: Disclose the potential conflict of interest to the audit committee and recuse themselves from further involvement in the audit. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Adjust the audit report to mitigate the impact of the fraud on the overall assessment of the organization''s internal controls. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.', 'The IS auditor has a professional obligation to report the fraud to the appropriate authorities within the organization, regardless of any personal relationships. Ethical conduct and objectivity are paramount.', 'See reasoning above for explanation of correct vs incorrect choices', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (C): Report the fraud to the appropriate authorities within the organization, regardless of the personal relationship.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation contro