icate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Implement FDE on all servers storing sensitive data. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Change the encryption algorithm to a more modern standard. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Increase the key length for file-level encryption. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
  ('CISA-00386', 5, 'Medium', 'Cloud Security', 'A company has migrated its applications and data to a cloud service provider (CSP). During a CISA audit, the auditor notes that the service level agreement (SLA) with the CSP does not clearly define the responsibilities for data backup and recovery. What should the auditor recommend FIRST?', 'Implement a secondary backup solution independent of the CSP.', 'Negotiate a revised SLA with the CSP to clearly define data backup and recovery responsibilities.', 'Implement data loss prevention (DLP) tools within the cloud environment.', 'Conduct a penetration test of the cloud environment to assess its security posture.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Negotiate a revised SLA with the CSP to clearly define data backup and recovery responsibilities.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''