  ('CISA-00388', 5, 'Medium', 'Physical Security Controls', 'An auditor is reviewing the physical security of a data center. The auditor notes that the data center uses biometric access control, but the backup generator is located outside the data center perimeter, without any physical security controls. What should the auditor recommend?', 'Implement biometric access control for the backup generator room.', 'Relocate the backup generator inside the data center perimeter.', 'Implement physical security controls, such as surveillance cameras and access controls, for the backup generator room.', 'Reduce the sensitivity of data processed during backup generator operation.', 'C', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (C): Implement physical security controls, such as surveillance cameras and access controls, for the backup generator room.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ 