  ('CISA-00401', 1, 'Hard', 'Audit Reporting', 'An IS auditor discovers a material weakness in internal control over financial reporting during an audit. Management has agreed to remediate the weakness within three months. Which of the following is the MOST appropriate way for the IS auditor to report this finding?', 'Issue an unqualified opinion, but include a separate paragraph noting the material weakness and management''s remediation plan.', 'Issue a qualified opinion, stating that the financial statements are fairly presented except for the effects of the material weakness.', 'Issue an adverse opinion, stating that the financial statements are not fairly presented due to the material weakness.', 'Issue an unqualified opinion if management acknowledges the weakness and has a remediation plan in place, without mentioning the weakness in the report.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Issue a qualified opinion, stating that the financial statements are fairly presented except for the effects of the material weakness.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as 