  ('CISA-00408', 5, 'Medium', 'Data Loss Prevention (DLP)', 'During a CISA review of a financial institution, the auditor discovers that a newly implemented Data Loss Prevention (DLP) system is generating a high volume of false positives related to employee emails containing numerical data. The DLP rules are triggering alerts on legitimate business communications, causing user frustration and hindering productivity. What is the MOST appropriate action for the auditor to take?', 'Recommend immediately disabling the DLP system until the rules can be refined to reduce false positives.', 'Review the DLP system''s configuration, rule sets, and exception handling processes in collaboration with the IT security team.', 'Report the high volume of false positives to senior management and recommend increased security awareness training for employees.', 'Verify the DLP system is capturing all data flows and enforce stricter controls on email communication content regardless of user impact.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Review the DLP system''s configuration, rule sets, and exception handling processes in collaboration with the IT security team.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk 