  ('CISA-00409', 5, 'Medium', 'Physical Security Controls', 'An auditor is performing a review of physical security controls at a data center. The data center utilizes biometric access control for entry. The auditor observes that the biometric scanners frequently fail to recognize authorized personnel, resulting in long queues and employee frustration. What is the auditor''s BEST course of action?', 'Recommend replacing the biometric system with a simpler access control method, such as key cards.', 'Review the biometric system''s maintenance logs, calibration procedures, and backup power systems.', 'Report the frequent failures to senior management and recommend disciplinary action for the vendor responsible.', 'Verify that all employees have been properly trained on using the biometric scanners and follow the correct procedures.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Review the biometric system''s maintenance logs, calibration procedures, and backup power systems.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Recommend replacing the biometric system with a simpler access control method, such as key cards. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option C: Report the frequent failures to senior management and recommend disciplinary action for the vendor responsible. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option D: Verify that all employees have been properly trained on using the biometric scanners and follow the correct procedures. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.', 'The best course of action is to review the system''s maintenance logs, calibration procedures, and backup power systems. This will help identify potential issues with the biometric scanners, such as inadequate maintenance, calibration drift, or power-related problems. Understanding the root cause is crucial before recommending drastic measures or assigning blame.', 'See reasoning above for explanation of correct vs incorrect choices', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Review the biometric system''s maintenance logs, calibration procedures, and backup power systems.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their