  ('CISA-00434', 4, 'Medium', 'Business Continuity Planning', 'During a review of an organization''s business continuity plan (BCP), the IS auditor discovers that the plan does not include procedures for restoring critical applications in the cloud environment. The auditor should FIRST:', 'Recommend an immediate update of the BCP to include cloud-specific restoration procedures.', 'Assess the organization''s dependency on cloud-based applications and their criticality to business operations.', 'Evaluate the cloud provider''s BCP and service level agreements (SLAs).', 'Conduct a business impact analysis (BIA) to identify all critical cloud-based applications.', 'B', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (B): Assess the organization''s dependency on cloud-based applications and their criticality to business operations.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS 