th proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountability for remediation • Audit trail for compliance purposes • Basis for future follow-up audits  ❌ INCORRECT OPTIONS - Why They''re Wrong:  Option A: Recommend that the company immediately implement a risk assessment process for incident response. → This approach either ignores the issue, escalates prematurely without documentation, or follows an unstructured process that creates audit gaps. Auditors must always follow structured procedures.  Option B: Assess the effectiveness of the incident response plan without considering the risk assessment. → This option misses the audit objective or applies the wrong standard. Audit procedures must be aligned with scope and audit standards (ISACA, COBIT).  Option C: Expand the scope of the audit to include a detailed risk assessment. → This might be a procedural step but not the complete or correct response. Context matters in audit decisions.'),
  ('CISA-00470', 1, 'Medium', 'Audit Reporting', 'During an audit of a data center''s physical security, the IS auditor observes that the fire suppression system has not been tested in over two years, despite manufacturer recommendations for annual testing. This represents a significant risk to business continuity. In the audit report, the IS auditor should:', 'Recommend immediate testing and include a detailed description of the potential impact on business continuity.', 'Simply state that the fire suppression system has not been tested according to manufacturer recommendations.', 'Assign a low-risk rating to the finding since fires are infrequent.', 'Exclude the finding from the report, as it is a physical security matter and not directly related to information systems.', 'A', '✅ CORRECT ANSWER (A): Recommend immediate testing and include a detailed description of the potential impact on business continuity.  COMPREHENSIVE EXPLANATION: This answer reflects best practices in IT audit methodology. The auditor must follow a structured approach when identifying control weaknesses or compliance issues. Proper documentation and escalation ensure that findings are recorded accurately and stakeholders can take corrective action within appropriate timeframes.  REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE: A large financial institution undergoes an audit of their payment processing system. The auditor identifies that critical reconciliation controls are manual and lack proper segregation of duties. Instead of just noting the issue, the auditor formally documents the finding, rates its severity (High - potential for fraud), and recommends implementation of automated controls with proper authorization workflows. This structured approach ensures management acknowledges the risk and allocates resources for remediation.  WHY THIS MATTERS: In audit work, how you communicate findings is as important as what you find. Proper reporting ensures: • Management understands the business impact • Clear accountabil